[~sjones] Thanks for the catch. It appears the bug would actually *allow* the configuration when there's an existing value.  
[~zhill] [~swathi]  Can you confirm that we don't allow changing an existing 'blockstoragemanager' property (unless SC is re-registered)?

Here's the proposed diff. The previous fix will return "" instead of "<unset>" for empty property.

{code:java}
     public void fireChange(ConfigurableProperty t, String newValue) throws ConfigurablePropertyException {
       String existingValue = (String) t.getValue();
-      if (existingValue != null && !"<unset>".equals(existingValue)) {
+      if (existingValue != null && !"".equals(existingValue)) {
         if (newValue != null && !newValue.equals(existingValue)) {
           throw new ConfigurablePropertyException(
               "Cannot change extant storage backend configuration. You must deregister all SCs in the partition before you can change the configuration value");

{code}

Verified, repeating [~spark]'s commands from above, but with euca-describe-properties --> euctl.

No <unset> anymore, just blank.

{code}
[root@d-01 ~]# euctl -U https://10.111.1.71:8773/services/Empyrean services.database.worker.keyname
services.database.worker.keyname =
[root@d-01 ~]# euctl -U https://10.111.1.71:8773/services/Empyrean one.storage.autosnapshots
one.storage.autosnapshots =
{code}

...and just checking that populated properties still show up:

{code}
[root@d-01 ~]# euctl -U https://10.111.1.71:8773/services/Empyrean one.storage.chapuser
one.storage.chapuser = CI-4011
{code}
